<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-156-478  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 156 478.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Computers  Jan 1990 v39 n1 p47(16).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Performance analysis of a generalized concurrent error detectionprocedure. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blough, Douglas M.; Masson, Gerald M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A general procedure for error detection in complex systems, thedata block capture and analysis monitoring process, is developedthat detects errors that may be caused by any internal or externalsoftware or hardware fault source.andP;  The fault mechanismsthemselves are often difficult to isolate, but the new procedurecan isolate a broad range of errors through determining anydeviations from normal system performance.andP;  The detection processconsists of capturing blocks of data being monitored and analyzingeach block for deviations that evidence faults.andP;  The performanceof linear, quadratic and logarithmic data analysis algorithms indetecting errors, the number of false alarms per actual errorcaught and the expectation and latency variations in errordetection are analyzed.andP;  The procedure can detect almost 90percent of errors with reasonable false alarm production anddetection latency.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Error AnalysisError TrappingNew TechniqueAlgorithm AnalysisPerformance MeasurementConcurrency ControlProcessor ArchitectureParallel ProcessingFailure Prediction.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   A concurrent monitor employing the data block capture and analysisprocess. (chart)A continuous Markov model. (chart)Data analysis algorithm execution times. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>